Used method `#completeOnTimeout(T value, long timeout, TimeUnit unit)` accepts value instead of some sort of supplier. This means that this value is computed before passing it into the method.

For case of executing some logic only upon timeout - `#get(long timeout, TimeUnit unit)` can be utilized.

Simplified version of the code:
```
try {
    CompletableFuture.runAsync(() -&gt; {
        System.out.println(&quot;async operation&quot;);
    }).get(1, TimeUnit.SECONDS);
} catch (TimeoutException e) {
    System.out.println(&quot;timeout happens&quot;);
}
```

Such approach will allow code execution upon encountering TimeoutException, which is thrown when future is not completed in specified time

