Does not throws `NullPointerException` if str is null, since [`Object.equals()`][1] returns false if arg is `null`.

the other construct `str.equals(&quot;&quot;)` would throw the dreaded `NullPointerException`. Some might consider bad form using a String literal as the object upon wich `equals()` is called but it does the job. 

