A Log4j [`Message`](https://logging.apache.org/log4j/2.x/log4j-api/apidocs/org/apache/logging/log4j/message/Message.html) is composed of:
 - a format and some parameters, which are interpolated to give you a formatted message. In your case it is:
   ```
   Initiating transaction rollback on application exception
   ```
 - an optional `Throwable` that is formatted similarly to `Throwable#printStackTrace()`:
   ```
   javax.jms.IllegalStateException: JMS-131: Session is closed
       at oracle.jms.AQjmsError.throwIllegalStateEx(AQjmsError.java:514) ~[aqapi-12.2.0.1.0.jar:?]
       at oracle.jms.AQjmsSession.checkSessionStarted(AQjmsSession.java:5521) ~[aqapi-12.2.0.1.0.jar:?]
       at oracle.jms.AQjmsSession.getTransacted(AQjmsSession.java:1015) ~[aqapi-12.2.0.1.0.jar:?]
   ```

The `RegexFilter` (cf. [documentation](https://logging.apache.org/log4j/2.x/manual/filters.html#RegexFilter)) only matches the formatted (or unformatted) message. The throwable is not used by this filter or any other of the standard filters.

Fortunately Log4j Core is very extensible and writing a new filter is a couple dozen lines:
```lang-java
@Plugin(name = &quot;ThrowableMessageFilter&quot;, category = Node.CATEGORY, elementType = Filter.ELEMENT_TYPE)
public class ThrowableMessageFilter extends AbstractFilter {

    @PluginFactory
    public static ThrowableMessageFilter createFilter(@PluginAttribute(&quot;regex&quot;) final String regex,
            @PluginAttribute(&quot;onMatch&quot;) final Result onMatch, @PluginAttribute(&quot;onMismatch&quot;) final Result onMismatch) {
        if (regex == null) {
            LOGGER.error(&quot;A regular expression must be provided for ThrowableMessageFilter&quot;);
            return null;
        }
        return new ThrowableMessageFilter(Pattern.compile(regex), onMatch, onMismatch);
    }

    private final Pattern pattern;

    private ThrowableMessageFilter(final Pattern pattern, final Result onMatch, final Result onMismatch) {
        super(onMatch, onMismatch);
        this.pattern = pattern;
    }

    private Result filter(final String message) {
        if (message == null) {
            return onMismatch;
        }
        final Matcher m = pattern.matcher(message);
        return m.matches() ? onMatch : onMismatch;
    }

    @Override
    public Result filter(LogEvent event) {
        final Throwable t = event.getThrown();
        return t != null ? filter(t.getMessage()) : onMismatch;
    }
}
```

You can then use it as:
```lang-xml
&lt;Logger name=&quot;oracle.jms.AQjmsError&quot; additivity=&quot;false&quot;&gt;
  &lt;AppenderRef ref=&quot;OtherFile&quot;&gt;
    &lt;ThrowableMessageFilter regex=&quot;.*JMS-131.*&quot;
                            onMatch=&quot;ACCEPT&quot;
                            onMismatch=&quot;DENY&quot;/&gt;
  &lt;/AppenderRef&gt;
&lt;/Logger&gt;
```
&lt;/Logger&gt;

**Edit:** For a temporary solution you can also use `ScriptFilter` (cf. [documentation](https://logging.apache.org/log4j/2.x/manual/filters.html#Script)). To use it you need:
 * a scripting engine like [Nashorn](https://github.com/openjdk/nashorn), which was available up to JRE 14 and is available standalone for JRE 15+,
 * add the scripting language used to the list of allowed languages by listing it in the system property `log4j2.scriptEnableLanguages` (e.g. by adding `-Dlog4j2.scriptEnableLanguages=javascript` to the JVM arguments),
 * write a script to match your exception, e.g.:
   ```lang-xml
   &lt;ScriptFilter onMatch=&quot;ACCEPT&quot; onMismatch=&quot;DENY&quot;&gt;
     &lt;Script language=&quot;javascript&quot;&gt;&lt;![CDATA[
       var t = logEvent.getThrown();
       if (t != null) {
         var m = t.getMessage();
         m != null ? m.contains(&quot;JMS-131&quot;) : false;
       } else {
         false;
       }
     ]]&gt;&lt;/Script&gt;
   &lt;/ScriptFilter&gt;
   ```

